{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01AguaB7sk9rQnxSzSJ61zDx","type":"tool_result","content":"# Vector Databases\n\nA vector database stores data as high-dimensional vectors (embeddings) and enables fast similarity search. They are a key component in [RAG](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) pipelines, recommendation systems, and semantic search.\n\n## Popular Options\n\n- **ChromaDB** — open-source, easy to set up, Python-native\n- **Pinecone** — managed service, scales automatically\n- **Weaviate** — open-source, supports hybrid search (vector + keyword)\n- **Qdrant** — open-source, Rust-based, high performance\n---\n# Retrieval-Augmented Generation\n\nRetrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a technique that enhances LLM responses by retrieving relevant documents from an external knowledge base before generating an answer. Instead of relying solely on the model's training data, RAG grounds responses in real, up-to-date documents.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. A user asks a question\n2. The system searches a document store (e.g. a [vector database](vector-databases.md), keyword index) for relevant chunks\n3. Those chunks are injected into the LLM prompt as context\n4. The LLM generates an answer grounded in the retrieved documents\n---\n# Agent Eval Harness\n\nA framework for evaluating AI agent skill quality through automated testing, judge scoring, and iterative optimization.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. **eval.yaml** — defines execution mode, dataset schema, output descriptions, judges, models, and thresholds\n2. **Dataset** — test cases with realistic inputs for the skill\n3. **Judges** — automated scorers that rate skill outputs against criteria\n4. **Run** — executes the skill against test cases, scores with judges, reports results","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"aeb2d5e5-49d7-48c0-8570-3ae359065cfe","uuid":"a650c7ea-c22b-416b-8b73-03848faca44a","timestamp":"2026-07-09T15:36:01.475Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"# Vector Databases\n\nA vector database stores data as high-dimensional vectors (embeddings) and enables fast similarity search. They are a key component in [RAG](retrieval-augmented-generation.md) pipelines, recommendation systems, and semantic search.\n\n## Popular Options\n\n- **ChromaDB** — open-source, easy to set up, Python-native\n- **Pinecone** — managed service, scales automatically\n- **Weaviate** — open-source, supports hybrid search (vector + keyword)\n- **Qdrant** — open-source, Rust-based, high performance\n---\n# Retrieval-Augmented Generation\n\nRetrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a technique that enhances LLM responses by retrieving relevant documents from an external knowledge base before generating an answer. Instead of relying solely on the model's training data, RAG grounds responses in real, up-to-date documents.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. A user asks a question\n2. The system searches a document store (e.g. a [vector database](vector-databases.md), keyword index) for relevant chunks\n3. Those chunks are injected into the LLM prompt as context\n4. The LLM generates an answer grounded in the retrieved documents\n---\n# Agent Eval Harness\n\nA framework for evaluating AI agent skill quality through automated testing, judge scoring, and iterative optimization.\n\n## How It Works\n\n1. **eval.yaml** — defines execution mode, dataset schema, output descriptions, judges, models, and thresholds\n2. **Dataset** — test cases with realistic inputs for the skill\n3. **Judges** — automated scorers that rate skill outputs against criteria\n4. **Run** — executes the skill against test cases, scores with judges, reports results","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
